eventData.headline: Alexander Hamilton Society
eventData.description:
The Alexander Hamilton Society (AHS) is a non-partisan, not-for-profit, national organization that seeks to identify, educate, and launch young men and women into foreign policy and national security careers imbued with the Hamiltonian perspective of strong and principled American leadership in global affairs.

Founded in March 2010 by Professor Aaron Friedberg of Princeton University, Daniel Blumenthal of the American Enterprise Institute, and Roy Katzovicz of Saddle Point Group LLC, we were established to confront U.S. foreign, economic, and national security policy failures at their source — American universities — and to provide our students with the experiences they would otherwise not gain, in all the fields from which they will influence U.S. policy. We supply what American higher education lacks: vital, constructive programming that is critical to the intellectual and professional development of a new generation of American leaders. With the world more chaotic and dangerous today than it has been in a half-century, we seed the ground for the future of American foreign policy.

Grounded in a strong and growing national foundation of student-led campus chapters, our network is central to the revitalization of our foreign policy. It acts as a bridge for our student leaders to promising internships, graduate programs, and professional opportunities in the worlds of academia, business, finance, policymaking, politics, and journalism. Our robust professional chapters in New York and Washington are convening vehicles for our members to meet like-minded peers and hear from our thought and political leaders, and our distinguished board of advisors assists us in maintaining the integrity of our programs. While our focus is on the long term, our alumni have already achieved significant influence in their professional pursuits, building the bench of talented people looking to serve the country over the course of their lives and careers.  

Join our Info Session for the Alexander Hamilton Society!

eventData.headline: Yale Shakespeare Club
eventData.description:
The Yale Shakespeare Club seeks to foster a love of Shakespeare’s works. Both long-time bardolators and Shakespeare novices are welcome to explore together the “infinite variety” of Shakespeare through many media, such as reading, film, scholarship, and performance. We also facilitate frequent, low-stress Shakespeare performances on campus for anyone to enjoy or perform—the best way to fall in love with the bard.

Come read some Shakespeare, watch some clips, have a nerdy discussion, and learn about the Yale Shakespeare Club!

eventData.headline: Undergrad Chapter of iCure Health
eventData.description:
Yale Undergraduate Chapter of iCure Health is part of a global non-profit that provides general education on preventive medicine as a means to combat chronic diseases, such as heart disease, diabetes, and cancer.

Are you interested in prevention of disease? Come learn more about iCure Health and the current projects we are working on! We will have trivia about prevention and other fun activities.

eventData.headline: Society of Women Engineers
eventData.description:
We are a group of women and gender minorities passionate about engineering. We strive to make sure all women and gender minorities feel welcomed, empowered, and thrive in engineering at Yale. Our activities include attending the SWE conference, professional events with companies, and fun events like gingerbread house decorating!

Come play games and learn about Yale Engineering and STEM!

eventData.headline: Grad-Undergrad Mentorship Initiative
eventData.description:
GUMI (Grad-Undergrad Mentorship Initiative) is a committee under the Yale Undergrad Research Association. We maintain a database of over 350 grad student mentors and create resources/host events to facilitate mentor-mentee interactions.

We will have a slideshow presentation outlining all of the mentorship options at Yale, with a specific focus on our database/Initiative. This event will be co-hosted by Dr. Karin Gosselink and the Academic Strategies Office, and they will also go into detail about the mentorship opportunities available through their office. There will also be time for questions at the end of the event/presentation for prefrosh to ask and possibly a breakout room activity.

eventData.headline: Yale Undergrad. Science Olympiad
eventData.description:
Yale Undergraduate Science Olympiad hosts an annual Science Olympiad College Invitational for high school students, an officially recognized tournament by SOINC.

This is an informal opportunity to chat with current board members about their experiences planning and running YUSO, the community behind it, and what positions are open for incoming board members next academic year.

eventData.headline: Chi Alpha Christian Fellowship
eventData.description:
Yale Chi Alpha is a Christian community on campus. We have weekly large group meetings we call TNL (Tuesday Night Live), weekly Core Groups, a Fall Retreat, and other fun things that happen throughout the semester. Our three core values are that students would have real devotion, real community, and real responsibility.

Meet the students within Chi Alpha! Not only will you get to meet our Core Group leaders, but some of the first years within our group will be there too as well as some of the Chi Alpha staff members. Ask any questions you want, hangout, and maybe even play some games with our students!

eventData.headline: Yale International Relations Association
eventData.description:
The Yale International Relations Association (YIRA) is the largest undergraduate organization on Yale's campus. If you're interested in anything from traveling the world to speaking at the UN, from designing websites to teaching high-schoolers, or from model UN to writing about global affairs, then YIRA has a home for you!

Game Night with YIRA:
Join us for a fun, casual night of virtual games—we'll be playing GeoGuessr, Among Us, Skribbl.io, JackBox, and more! Stay for as long or as short as you’d like!

Come learn about Matriculate’s mission and values! Current High School Fellows are especially encouraged to attend!

eventData.headline: Yale Precision Marching Band
eventData.description:
The YPMB is Yale's premier "marching" band, and we invite all students (and even faculty) to join us!  

Do you play an instrument? Great! Show off your skills while playing alongside YPMB members who are also in other groups, like the Yale Concert Band and the Symphony Orchestra. Always wanted to learn how to play one? Awesome! We can hook you up with an instrument and a teacher. Love appreciating music, but not playing it? Incredible! All of our music is student arranged (that's right-we get to play all the pop, rock, hip-hop, etc. music we want!)! Love the vibe of the band, but looking for a virtual art outlet? Join the Squids, who put together all of our props for halftime shows (re: our 40ft bald eagle prop). Got a good sense of humor? Help write and put together our halftime shows-every member of the band has input!

We could go on for pages trying to tell you what we are. You’d be best off to show up and find out, really. You won’t be disappointed!

Create a YPMB Halftime Show!
Join the Yale Precision Marching Band's Halftime Show Advisors to learn how our shows are put together! We will be working on a show we’ll be performing this fall during a football game, and we’re looking for your input, creativity, and humor. Come help us create a show that you could perform your first semester!
